Welcome to the group.  Although I have not studied the history of
English spelling per se, it appears to me that we got into this mess due
to the wide distribution of English speakers around the world, the
insistence on spelling standardization and the lack of any mechanism
that could enforce updated spelling changes to keep the written language
in sync with the spoken tongue.  It is my understanding that some
countries, such as Germany, do have such a mechanism, and about every 50
years or so, they update standard spellings to bring them back in line
with current pronunciations.  I can&#39;t see any way this could be done
with English.  

Your prediction that one dialect in English may win out over others due
to the impact of the media does not seem particularly likely to me.  I
can listen to Peter Jennings for years, but that has not affected my own
idiolect as far as I can tell.

Paige Gabhart

&quot;I despise a world which does not feel that music is a higher revelation
than all wisdom and philosophy.&quot; 
-Ludwig van Beethoven 

